        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1969-09-16T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1969-09-16T00:00:00-05:00" n="37"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d37">
                <head>37. Memorandum From the President’s Assistant for National Security Affairs
                        (<persName corresp="#p_KHA1" type="from">Kissinger</persName>) to the
                    Chairman of the <gloss target="#t_NSSM1">NSSM</gloss> 27 Steering Group
                        (<persName corresp="#p_BWG1" type="to">Brown</persName>)<note n="1"
                        type="source" xml:id="d37fn1">Source: National Archives, <persName
                            corresp="#p_NRM1">Nixon</persName> Presidential Materials, <gloss
                            target="#t_NSC1">NSC</gloss> Files, <gloss target="#t_NSC1">NSC</gloss>
                        Institutional Files (H-Files), Box H–041, Review Group Meeting—<gloss
                            target="#t_NSSM1">NSSM</gloss> 27 Korea 2/6/70. Secret. Copies were sent
                        to <persName corresp="#p_RWP1">Rogers</persName>, <persName
                            corresp="#p_LMR1">Laird</persName>, <persName corresp="#p_HRM1"
                            >Helms</persName>, Mayo, Hannah, <persName corresp="#p_SF1"
                            >Shakespeare</persName>, and <persName corresp="#p_WEG1"
                            >Wheeler</persName>.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>Washington</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian"
                            when="1969-09-16">September 16, 1969</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <list type="subject">
                    <head>SUBJECT</head>
                    <item>Guidance on <gloss target="#t_NSSM1">NSSM</gloss> 27</item>
                </list>
                <p>The President has directed the completion of the <gloss target="#t_NSSM1"
                        >NSSM</gloss> 27<note n="2" xml:id="d37fn2">
                        <ref target="#d2">Document 2</ref>.</note> evaluation of U.S. policy and
                    program alternatives for Korea. In light of <gloss target="#t_NSDM1"
                        >NSDM</gloss> 4,<note n="3" xml:id="d37fn3">See <ref target="#d2fn3"
                            >footnote 3, Document 2</ref>. <gloss target="#t_NSDM1">NSDM</gloss> 4
                        was revised on September 4; see <ref target="frus1969-76v02#d71">
                            <hi rend="italic">Foreign Relations,</hi> 1969–1976, volume II,
                            Organization and Management of U.S. Foreign Policy, 1969–1972, Document
                            71</ref>.</note> he expects that this study will: <list>
                        <item>—present the alternatives considered in the form of five year plans
                            for U.S. policy and programs toward Korea.</item>
                        <item>—include a description of the key program and budgetary decisions to
                            implement a given plan and their timing over the next five years.</item>
                    </list>
                </p>
                <p>After being briefed on the <gloss target="#t_NSSM1">NSSM</gloss> 27 summary,<note
                        n="4" xml:id="d37fn4">
                        <ref target="#d27">Document 27</ref>.</note> the President also decided
                    that: <list>
                        <item>—U.S. and <gloss target="#t_ROK1">ROK</gloss> force structures posed
                            in Alternative 1 of the <gloss target="#t_NSSM1">NSSM</gloss> 27 summary
                            need not be considered further.</item>
                        <item>—<gloss target="#t_ROK1">ROK</gloss> air and naval forces,
                            particularly fast patrol boats, will be strengthened, if necessary, to
                            meet the threat of North Korean “hit and run” attacks.</item>
                        <item>—U.S. economic assistance to Korea may be maintained if it will in
                            fact strengthen Korea’s prospects for rapid economic growth.</item>
                    </list>
                </p>
                <p>I understand that <gloss target="#t_IG1">IG</gloss>/<gloss target="#t_EA1"
                        >EA</gloss>’s comments on the <gloss target="#t_NSSM1">NSSM</gloss> 27
                    summary will be available shortly. When they are submitted, the study should be
                    revised as appropriate in cooperation with my Program Analysis staff. The <gloss
                        target="#t_NSSM1">NSSM</gloss> 27 summary should be completed by October 15,
                    1969 in preparation for another National Security Council meeting on Korea.<note
                        n="5" xml:id="d37fn5">No record of an additional <gloss target="#t_NSC1"
                            >NSC</gloss> meeting on Korea in 1969 was found. The next <gloss
                            target="#t_NSC1">NSC</gloss> meeting on Korea was held on March 4, 1970
                        (see <ref target="#d55">Document 55</ref>).</note>
                </p>
            </div>
